   =20
      Masterly stock manipulations
   =20
 =20
Here=E2=80=99s a=C2=A0scam. You start, or gain control of, a tiny company w=
ith publicly traded stock. The company doesn=E2=80=99t do much; its stock t=
rades for a few pennies a share at most. You own most of the shares. You ma=
ke yourself (or your friend) the chief executive officer of the company, an=
d you have the company put out a bunch of press releases saying =E2=80=9Cwe=
=E2=80=99ve found a cure for cancer=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re pivo=
ting to crypto=E2=80=9D or whatever. Maybe you and your friends buy some mo=
re shares to make the stock go up. People notice the press releases and the=
 stock going up, so they start buying the stock and it goes up more. You se=
ll your stock as they buy it. You have taken the stock of a worthless compa=
ny, briefly tricked people into thinking it=E2=80=99s valuable, and then=C2=
=A0dumped the stock on them.As a general form of scam this is very popular =
and, apparently, lucrative, and so of course there are rules to prevent it.=
 For one thing it is illegal and if you do it you can go to prison, though =
that is only the very last line of defense and not everyone gets caught. Th=
ere are other defenses. For instance, in the U.S., if you control a company=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0including just by owning a lot of its stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
there are restrictions on your ability to sell it. Even if you aren=E2=80=
=99t doing a scam, I mean, if you own 50% of a penny-stock company you can=
=E2=80=99t just dump all your shares anonymously in the stock market in a w=
eek. Your stock is =E2=80=9Crestricted,=E2=80=9D and generally speaking you=
 need to register your sales of restricted stock, file a prospectus with th=
e Securities and Exchange Commission, disclose that you=E2=80=99re selling,=
 etc.[4] One purpose of these rules is to make sure that the company disclo=
ses all relevant information about itself to people who might buy the stock=
. But another purpose is just to flag to everyone that you =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
he big shareholder =E2=80=94=C2=A0are selling. =E2=80=9CHuh, that=E2=80=99s=
 odd,=E2=80=9D they might think, =E2=80=9Cthis company just put out a press=
 release saying that it cured cancer, but the CEO is selling all of her sto=
ck. Perhaps something is amiss!=E2=80=9D And then they don=E2=80=99t buy it=
.Of course if you are doing a scam anyway, you might decide to ignore these=
 rules. Sell your stock without filing a registration statement, why not. B=
ut there are further defenses. Companies hire transfer agents to keep track=
 of their stock ownership, and the transfer agent =E2=80=94=C2=A0generally =
a reputable independent company =E2=80=94=C2=A0will check whether stock is =
=E2=80=9Crestricted=E2=80=9D and not let you sell it freely if it is.=C2=A0=
Brokerage firms are going to ask questions and do checks; if you are the CE=
O and 50% shareholder of a company they won=E2=80=99t let you just dump you=
r stock into the market. The intermediaries in the financial system are sup=
posed to prevent this scam.So if you are determined to do this scam, you mi=
ght have to do some subsidiary scams to trick the intermediaries into think=
ing that you don=E2=80=99t own your stock, or you don=E2=80=99t control the=
 company. Instead of you owning 50% of the stock, pretend that 12 apparentl=
y unconnected people each own 4% or so;=C2=A0they=C2=A0sell the stock (and =
you get the money). That sort of thing. And while there is a system of regu=
lated legal intermediaries =E2=80=94=C2=A0transfer agents, legitimate broke=
rs =E2=80=94=C2=A0who facilitate stock sales and who are supposed to be on =
guard against scammers, there is another system of=C2=A0illegal=C2=A0interm=
ediaries who help people do exactly this scam.=C2=A0Here are=C2=A0an SEC en=
forcement action=C2=A0and related criminal charges=C2=A0against some people=
 accused of running one of these intermediaries:The Securities and Exchange=
 Commission [yesterday] announced an emergency action charging nine individ=
uals, including a public company chairman, for their participation in long-=
running fraudulent schemes that collectively generated hundreds of millions=
 of dollars from unlawful stock sales and caused significant harm to retail=
 investors in the United States and around the world. The SEC has obtained =
emergency relief in court, including an order to freeze the defendants=E2=
=80=99 assets.According to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint unsealed today, Cana=
dian resident Frederick L. Sharp masterminded a complex scheme from 2011 to=
 2019 in which he and his associates =E2=80=93 Canadian residents Zhiying Y=
vonne Gasarch and Courtney Kelln =E2=80=93 enabled control persons of micro=
cap companies whose stock was publicly traded in the U.S. securities market=
s to conceal their control and ownership of huge amounts of penny stock.=C2=
=A0 They then surreptitiously dumped the stock into the U.S. markets in vio=
lation of federal securities laws.=C2=A0 The services Sharp and his associa=
tes allegedly provided included furnishing networks of offshore shell compa=
nies to conceal stock ownership, arranging stock transfers and money transm=
ittals, and providing encrypted accounting and communications systems.=C2=
=A0 According to the complaint, Sharp and his associates facilitated over a=
 billion dollars in gross sales in hundreds of penny stock companies.The SE=
C=E2=80=99s complaint is delightful, because the way this business (alleged=
ly) works is not, like, a couple of guys in a room doing a scam. This is a =
big business of facilitating other people=E2=80=99s scams, so it has to hav=
e a certain amount of advertising and branding and customer service. And oh=
 boy does it:Sharp, who used the code name =E2=80=9CBond=E2=80=9D (styling =
himself after the fictional character James Bond), was the mastermind and l=
eader of the Sharp Group. Among other things, Sharp cultivated relationship=
s with the Sharp Group=E2=80=99s clients=E2=80=94that is, individuals seeki=
ng fraudulently to sell stock in the markets to retail investors=E2=80=94an=
d with various offshore trading platforms. Sharp also routinely served as a=
 liaison between dozens of clients (like the Veldhuis Control Group) and th=
e trading platforms (like Wintercap SA).=C2=A0During the period of the sche=
me detailed herein, Sharp described in a communication to a client the foll=
owing about the Sharp Group=E2=80=99s services: =E2=80=9CThe service provid=
ed is comprehensive; it is not limited to trading. It includes pyaments [si=
c], loans, private placements and keeping clients out of jail.=E2=80=9D (Em=
phasis added).Right, see, if you just want to do legal trading, you can go =
to Robinhood or whatever. If you want to do=C2=A0crime=C2=A0trading, you wi=
ll need a more full-service broker, one whose business includes keeping you=
 out of jail. Or trying to.Here is more on the alleged full service:Sharp o=
versaw the creation and deployment of various front companies, which served=
 as nominee shareholders used to disguise his clients=E2=80=99 stock owners=
hip and to sell stock surreptitiously.One of the services provided by the S=
harp Group was making available offshore corporate nominee shareholders and=
 individuals who would serve as the nominal owners of those entities. Sharp=
 installed these various nominal owners to pose as the beneficial owners of=
 the=C2=A0=C2=A0various entities that served as nominee shareholders. In ac=
tuality, these individuals did not own or control the stock held by the nom=
inee shareholders and generally had no role other than offering their names=
, passports, and signatures, which the Sharp Group used to incorporate and =
open accounts for the corporate nominees. In dealing with banks, brokerages=
, and other financial services providers, these individuals were held out a=
s actual beneficial owners. In this way, the Sharp Group kept the identitie=
s of control groups hidden, while fraudulently appearing to satisfy the com=
pliance requirements of the banking and securities firms where the Sharp Gr=
oup opened these accounts.Again the basic idea is that if you run a penny-s=
tock company and own a bunch of its stock, and you go to a brokerage to sel=
l the stock, the broker will stop you. But if you get a dozen random people=
 to open brokerage accounts saying that they own some of your stock, the br=
oker might let them sell. To do this you need a dozen random people to lend=
 their =E2=80=9Cnames, passports, and signatures=E2=80=9D to a crime, and y=
ou might have a hard time finding them. But it=E2=80=99s no problem for Bon=
d. That is the business he=E2=80=99s in.Obviously it=E2=80=99s a problem fo=
r you if you pretend to give your stock to those dozen random people and th=
ey sell it and keep the money.=C2=A0(What are you going to do, sue them?) F=
ortunately Bond has his Q accounting system to keep everything honest:Sharp=
 also hired and directed individuals who created and administered the Sharp=
 Group=E2=80=99s accounting system, which Sharp called =E2=80=9CQ=E2=80=9D =
(thereby expanding his James Bond affectations =E2=80=93 =E2=80=9CQ=E2=80=
=9D being another fictional character in James Bond). Given the extensive e=
fforts by the Sharp Group and its clients to conceal and obscure the actual=
 ownership and control of the stock they were surreptitiously selling, the =
Q system was essential in keeping track of the amounts of stock to be sold =
and the total proceeds being collected for each deal Sharp=E2=80=99s client=
s ran. Accordingly, the Sharp Group accounted for all of the nominee shareh=
olders=E2=80=99 assets in Q by tracking which of the nominee shareholders h=
eld which stocks (and which stocks=E2=80=99 sales proceeds) for which parti=
cular client or client group, like the Veldhuis Control Group. The Sharp Gr=
oup also relied on the Q system to calculate the commissions and fees it co=
llected for facilitating its clients=E2=80=99 illegal stock sales.=C2=A0I c=
annot resist=C2=A0people who do crimes, run their crimes like a legitimate =
business, and also play-act at being spies. Just an endlessly charming comb=
ination.=C2=A0But here is the very best part of this case:In 2002, Sharp wr=
ote a fictionalized book about securities fraud and money laundering in whi=
ch he described illegal conduct that parallels the Sharp Group=E2=80=99s bu=
siness model. Sharp=E2=80=99s book (Footloose: Charlie Smith=E2=80=99s Offs=
hore Chronicles) includes the following passage:=E2=80=9CEventually [the cl=
ient] took greater positions in the stocks, sharing the take with fewer par=
tners. This meant he had to disguise his shareholdings in order to avoid se=
curities disclosure requirements and trading restrictions.Offshore companie=
s were ideal for his purpose. They came from around the world with nominee =
directors, but were still subject to his control. The perfect situation for=
 his masterly stock manipulations.=E2=80=9DImagine being the SEC lawyer ass=
igned to read =E2=80=9CFootloose: Charlie Smith=E2=80=99s Offshore Chronicl=
es=E2=80=9D to prepare for this case. Or do you think some SEC lawyer was r=
eading =E2=80=9CFootloose: Charlie Smith=E2=80=99s Offshore Chronicles=E2=
=80=9D for pleasure[5] and thought =E2=80=9Chey this fictional account soun=
ds awfully realistic,=C2=A0I wonder if we should take a quick peek into thi=
s author=E2=80=9D? =E2=80=9CHis masterly stock manipulations,=E2=80=9D I lo=
ve it.=C2=A0
