      Object-fire-token-money
   =20
 =20
I have written several times about what I call the=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cobject-fir=
e-token-money=E2=80=9D NFT cycle: You acquire some work of art or other val=
uable cultural object (e.g. a  Banksy painting), you light it on fire, you =
create some electronic (or paper)=C2=A0certificate saying =E2=80=9CI promis=
e I destroyed this object,=E2=80=9D and then you sell the certificate=C2=A0=
to some crypto millionaire as its own art object, a =E2=80=9Cnon-fungible t=
oken=E2=80=9D that has some asserted artistic or scarcity or comedic value.=
 Last week I wrote about a woman who plans to be cremated, when she dies, w=
ith the only existing audio recording of J.D. Salinger. The audio recording=
 is, let us assume, a valuable cultural object that people would like to pa=
y money for (but can=E2=80=99t because she=E2=80=99s gonna burn it). But, I=
 said, a certificate that it was burned is also=C2=A0a valuable cultural ob=
ject, sort of, whatever, that people might also pay money for. If you burn=
=C2=A0a valuable cultural artifact, you get an NFT, which is also valuable.=
 This is how crypto economics works. I promise that I do not make the rules=
.Reader David Vasak emailed to point out that I was not thinking big enough=
:Surely you don't need a valuable cultural object to be burnt; just film a =
sufficiently well known person being cremated after their funeral and mint =
an NFT of that? Object - fire - token - money!I=E2=80=99m not sure you even=
 need the video! In the classic =E2=80=9Cobject-fire-token-money=E2=80=9D c=
ycle, the point of the video is to prove that the original object no longer=
 exists, so the token is the only remaining representation of the cultural =
artifact. I do not think that this makes very much sense, but it seems to b=
e how the NFT world operates. But if everyone knows that the original objec=
t no longer exists then you can dispense with the video, and the burning fo=
r that matter. For instance it is fairly clear that William Shakespeare is =
no longer alive. So if I sold an NFT =E2=80=9Cof=E2=80=9D William Shakespea=
re =E2=80=94=C2=A0a representation of Shakespeare on the blockchain =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the actual William Shakespeare could not pop up and say =E2=80=9Cn=
o I=E2=80=99m Shakespeare, not this token thing.=E2=80=9D[6] So Shakespeare=
-on-blockchain has exactly the same scarcity value as burnt-Banksy-on-block=
chain. More, really, because there are a lot of Banksy paintings that someo=
ne could burn, but only one Shakespeare.=E2=80=9CBut if you put =E2=80=98Sh=
akespeare=E2=80=99 on the blockchain,=E2=80=9D you say,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwhat =
connection does that have to the actual Shakespeare? Couldn=E2=80=99t anyon=
e else also put =E2=80=98Shakespeare=E2=80=99 on the blockchain, creating a=
n unlimited supply of unique tokens all asserting some totally insubstantia=
l=C2=A0link to Shakespeare? Doesn=E2=80=99t buying =E2=80=98Shakespeare=E2=
=80=99 on the blockchain confer absolutely no rights or benefits to the act=
ual Shakespeare or his works?=E2=80=9D Right!Men have died from time to tim=
e, and worms have eaten them, but not for NFTs. I=E2=80=99m sorry that this=
 is even stupider than my usual stupid NFT sections.
