yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> some more Say Technologies news</a> f=
rom this morning:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robinhood Mar=
kets Inc. agreed to buy Say Technologies, a tool for shareholder voting and=
 communication, in its first acquisition as a public company.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The approximately $140 million all-cash deal will give=
 Robinhood access to Say=E2=80=99s software, which helps company shareholde=
rs exercise their right to vote proxies and ask questions of management, ac=
cording to a blog post Tuesday. The announcement comes less than two weeks =
after Robinhood made its public trading debut.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Makes sense.=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100=
%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Masterly stock manipulations</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a=C2=A0scam. You start,=
 or gain control of, a tiny company with publicly traded stock. The company=
 doesn=E2=80=99t do much; its stock trades for a few pennies a share at mos=
t. You own most of the shares. You make yourself (or your friend) the chief=
 executive officer of the company, and you have the company put out a bunch=
 of press releases saying =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ve found a cure for cancer=E2=
=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re pivoting to crypto=E2=80=9D or whatever. M=
aybe you and your friends buy some more shares to make the stock go up. Peo=
ple notice the press releases and the stock going up, so they start buying =
the stock and it goes up more. You sell your stock as they buy it. You have=
 taken the stock of a worthless company, briefly tricked people into thinki=
ng it=E2=80=99s valuable, and then=C2=A0dumped the stock on them.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a general form of scam this is very popular and, =
apparently, lucrative, and so of course there are rules to prevent it. For =
one thing it is illegal and if you do it you can go to prison, though that =
is only the very last line of defense and not everyone gets caught. There a=
re other defenses. For instance, in the U.S., if you control a company =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0including just by owning a lot of its stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0ther=
e are restrictions on your ability to sell it. Even if you aren=E2=80=99t d=
oing a scam, I mean, if you own 50% of a penny-stock company you can=E2=80=
=99t just dump all your shares anonymously in the stock market in a week. Y=
our stock is =E2=80=9Crestricted,=E2=80=9D and generally speaking you need =
to register your sales of restricted stock, file a prospectus with the Secu=
rities and Exchange Commission, disclose that you=E2=80=99re selling, etc.[=
4] One purpose of these rules is to make sure that the company discloses al=
l relevant information about itself to people who might buy the stock. But =
another purpose is just to flag to everyone that you =E2=80=94=C2=A0the big=
 shareholder =E2=80=94=C2=A0are selling. =E2=80=9CHuh, that=E2=80=99s odd,=
=E2=80=9D they might think, =E2=80=9Cthis company just put out a press rele=
ase saying that it cured cancer, but the CEO is selling all of her stock. P=
erhaps something is amiss!=E2=80=9D And then they don=E2=80=99t buy it.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course if you are doing a scam anyway, you =
might decide to ignore these rules. Sell your stock without filing a regist=
ration statement, why not. But there are further defenses. Companies hire t=
ransfer agents to keep track of their stock ownership, and the transfer age=
nt =E2=80=94=C2=A0generally a reputable independent company =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
will check whether stock is =E2=80=9Crestricted=E2=80=9D and not let you se=
ll it freely if it is.=C2=A0Brokerage firms are going to ask questions and =
do checks; if you are the CEO and 50% shareholder of a company they won=E2=
=80=99t let you just dump your stock into the market. The intermediaries in=
 the financial system are supposed to prevent this scam.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">So if you are determined to do this scam, you might have to d=
o some subsidiary scams to trick the intermediaries into thinking that you =
don=E2=80=99t own your stock, or you don=E2=80=99t control the company. Ins=
tead of you owning 50% of the stock, pretend that 12 apparently unconnected=
 people each own 4% or so;=C2=A0<em>they=C2=A0</em>sell the stock (and you =
get the money). That sort of thing. And while there is a system of regulate=
d legal intermediaries =E2=80=94=C2=A0transfer agents, legitimate brokers =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0who facilitate stock sales and who are supposed to be on gua=
rd against scammers, there is another system of=C2=A0<em>illegal=C2=A0</em>=
intermediaries who help people do <em>exactly this scam</em>.=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/24703227.276523/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZX=
NzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS0xNDg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB584b852a" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">an SEC enforcement actio=
n</a>=C2=A0and related <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/24703227.276523/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1tYS9wci9mb3VyLW=
luZGl2aWR1YWxzLWNoYXJnZWQtbG9uZy1ydW5uaW5nLWdsb2JhbC1wdW1wLWFuZC1kdW1wLXNja=
GVtZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB646ae3e4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">criminal charges</a>=C2=A0against some peo=
ple accused of running one of these intermediaries:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission [yesterday] ann=
ounced an emergency action charging nine individuals, including a public co=
mpany chairman, for their participation in long-running fraudulent schemes =
that collectively generated hundreds of millions of dollars from unlawful s=
tock sales and caused significant harm to retail investors in the United St=
ates and around the world. The SEC has obtained emergency relief in court, =
including an order to freeze the defendants=E2=80=99 assets.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">According to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint unsealed today, =
Canadian resident Frederick L. Sharp masterminded a complex scheme from 201=
1 to 2019 in which he and his associates =E2=80=93 Canadian residents Zhiyi=
ng Yvonne Gasarch and Courtney Kelln =E2=80=93 enabled control persons of m=
icrocap companies whose stock was publicly traded in the U.S. securities ma=
rkets to conceal their control and ownership of huge amounts of penny stock=
.=C2=A0 They then surreptitiously dumped the stock into the U.S. markets in=
 violation of federal securities laws.=C2=A0 The services Sharp and his ass=
ociates allegedly provided included furnishing networks of offshore shell c=
ompanies to conceal stock ownership, arranging stock transfers and money tr=
ansmittals, and providing encrypted accounting and communications systems.=
=C2=A0 According to the complaint, Sharp and his associates facilitated ove=
r a billion dollars in gross sales in hundreds of penny stock companies.</p=
></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24703227.276523/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saX=
RpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMS9jb21wLXByMjAyMS0xNDgucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB311d1198" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">SEC=E2=80=99s complaint</a> is delightful, because the way this bu=
siness (allegedly) works is not, like, a couple of guys in a room doing a s=
cam. This is a big business of facilitating other people=E2=80=99s scams, s=
o it has to have a certain amount of advertising and branding and customer =
service. And oh boy does it:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sh=
arp, who used the code name =E2=80=9CBond=E2=80=9D (styling himself after t=
he fictional character James Bond), was the mastermind and leader of the Sh=
arp Group. Among other things, Sharp cultivated relationships with the Shar=
p Group=E2=80=99s clients=E2=80=94that is, individuals seeking fraudulently=
 to sell stock in the markets to retail investors=E2=80=94and with various =
offshore trading platforms. Sharp also routinely served as a liaison betwee=
n dozens of clients (like the Veldhuis Control Group) and the trading platf=
orms (like Wintercap SA).=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the =
period of the scheme detailed herein, Sharp described in a communication to=
 a client the following about the Sharp Group=E2=80=99s services: =E2=80=9C=
The service provided is comprehensive; it is not limited to trading. It inc=
ludes pyaments [sic], loans, private placements <strong>and keeping clients=
 out of jail</strong>.=E2=80=9D (Emphasis added).</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right, see, if you just want to do legal trading, you =
can go to Robinhood or whatever. If you want to do=C2=A0<em>crime=C2=A0</em=
>trading, you will need a more full-service broker, one whose business incl=
udes keeping you out of jail. Or trying to.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Here is more on the alleged full service:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Sharp oversaw the creation and deployment of various front comp=
anies, which served as nominee shareholders used to disguise his clients=E2=
=80=99 stock ownership and to sell stock surreptitiously.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">One of the services provided by the Sharp Group was making a=
vailable offshore corporate nominee shareholders and individuals who would =
serve as the nominal owners of those entities. Sharp installed these variou=
s nominal owners to pose as the beneficial owners of the=C2=A0=C2=A0various=
 entities that served as nominee shareholders. In actuality, these individu=
als did not own or control the stock held by the nominee shareholders and g=
enerally had no role other than offering their names, passports, and signat=
ures, which the Sharp Group used to incorporate and open accounts for the c=
orporate nominees. In dealing with banks, brokerages, and other financial s=
ervices providers, these individuals were held out as actual beneficial own=
ers. In this way, the Sharp Group kept the identities of control groups hid=
den, while fraudulently appearing to satisfy the compliance requirements of=
 the banking and securities firms where the Sharp Group opened these accoun=
ts.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again the basic idea is th=
at if you run a penny-stock company and own a bunch of its stock, and you g=
o to a brokerage to sell the stock, the broker will stop you. But if you ge=
t a dozen random people to open brokerage accounts saying that they own som=
e of your stock, the broker might let them sell. To do this you need a doze=
n random people to lend their =E2=80=9Cnames, passports, and signatures=E2=
=80=9D to a crime, and you might have a hard time finding them. But it=E2=
=80=99s no problem for Bond. That is the business he=E2=80=99s in.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously it=E2=80=99s a problem for you if you pre=
tend to give your stock to those dozen random people and they sell it and k=
eep the money.=C2=A0(What are you going to do, sue them?) Fortunately Bond =
has his Q accounting system to keep everything honest:</p><blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sharp also hired and directed individuals who creat=
ed and administered the Sharp Group=E2=80=99s accounting system, which Shar=
p called =E2=80=9CQ=E2=80=9D (thereby expanding his James Bond affectations=
 =E2=80=93 =E2=80=9CQ=E2=80=9D being another fictional character in James B=
ond). Given the extensive efforts by the Sharp Group and its clients to con=
ceal and obscure the actual ownership and control of the stock they were su=
rreptitiously selling, the Q system was essential in keeping track of the a=
mounts of stock to be sold and the total proceeds being collected for each =
deal Sharp=E2=80=99s clients ran. Accordingly, the Sharp Group accounted fo=
r all of the nominee shareholders=E2=80=99 assets in Q by tracking which of=
 the nominee shareholders held which stocks (and which stocks=E2=80=99 sale=
s proceeds) for which particular client or client group, like the Veldhuis =
Control Group. The Sharp Group also relied on the Q system to calculate the=
 commissions and fees it collected for facilitating its clients=E2=80=99 il=
legal stock sales.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I can=
not resist=C2=A0people who do crimes, run their crimes like a legitimate bu=
siness, and also play-act at being spies. Just an endlessly charming combin=
ation.=C2=A0But here is the very best part of this case:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2002, Sharp wrote a fictionalized book about s=
ecurities fraud and money laundering in which he described illegal conduct =
that parallels the Sharp Group=E2=80=99s business model. Sharp=E2=80=99s bo=
ok (<em>Footloose: Charlie Smith=E2=80=99s Offshore Chronicles</em>) includ=
es the following passage:</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CEventual=
ly [the client] took greater positions in the stocks, sharing the take with=
 fewer partners. This meant he had to disguise his shareholdings in order t=
o avoid securities disclosure requirements and trading restrictions.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Offshore companies were ideal for his purpose. Th=
ey came from around the world with nominee directors, but were still subjec=
t to his control. The perfect situation for his masterly stock manipulation=
s.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Imagine being the =
SEC lawyer assigned to read =E2=80=9CFootloose: Charlie Smith=E2=80=99s Off=
shore Chronicles=E2=80=9D to prepare for this case. Or do you think some SE=
C lawyer was reading =E2=80=9CFootloose: Charlie Smith=E2=80=99s Offshore C=
hronicles=E2=80=9D for pleasure[5] and thought =E2=80=9Chey this fictional =
account sounds awfully realistic,=C2=A0I wonder if we should take a quick p=
eek into this author=E2=80=9D? =E2=80=9CHis masterly stock manipulations,=
=E2=80=9D I love it.=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=
